Last year, when a series of former Facebook executives (http://a%20series%2=
0of%20former%20Facebook%20executives%20came%20forward%20to%20reveal%20misgi=
vings) came forward to reveal misgivings about the world that social media =
had created, few names resonated more loudly than Justin Rosenstein=E2=80=
=99s. Rosenstein, who helped to develop the Like button at Facebook and pre=
viously worked on Gmail chat at Google, told The Guardian that he had taken=
 several steps to eliminate social media distractions in his life, includin=
g limiting his time on Facebook and =E2=80=9Cbanning himself from Snapchat.=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CIt is very common,=E2=80=9D Rosenstein told the newspape=
r (http://told%20the%20newspaper) in October, =E2=80=9Cfor humans to develo=
p things with the best of intentions and for them to have unintended, negat=
ive consequences.=E2=80=9D

Half a year later, Rosenstein says he=E2=80=99s bringing his ideas about di=
gital distractions into his current product. Rosenstein is the co-founder a=
nd head of product at Asana, which makes software for tracking work (http:/=
/Asana,%20which%20makes%20software%20for%20tracking%20work) via to-do lists=
, Trello-like boards, and other tools. Today the company, which raised an a=
dditional $75 million in January and is now valued at $900 million, is anno=
uncing a new tool: Timeline (https://blog.asana.com/2018/03/new-asana-timel=
ine-view/), which lets workers quickly create and modify Gantt charts based=
 on the data they=E2=80=99ve already put into Asana.

As a successful gambit to get me to write about Gantt charts, Asana offered=
 Justin up for an interview about social media and his recent comments abou=
t its effect on our lives. You can read the whole thing here (https://www.t=
heverge.com/2018/3/28/17172404/justin-rosenstein-asana-social-media-faceboo=
k-timeline-gantt), but here's the key exchange:

Is social media good or bad?I think it=E2=80=99s good for the world on bala=
nce. The question is so complicated, it=E2=80=99s hard to compute. But the =
good parts of social media have become so taken for granted that we=E2=80=
=99ve stopped praising them. And the bad parts, people are starting to see =
for the first time. So people are like, =E2=80=9COh, it=E2=80=99s all terri=
ble.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s a very unbalanced perspective.You look at the =
#MeToo movement. That=E2=80=99s named after a hashtag. It=E2=80=99s this re=
ally important social movement that spread on the wings of social media. A =
hugely important, civilization-level conversation =E2=80=94 millions of peo=
ple in a week. That=E2=80=99s incredible! People weren=E2=80=99t like, =E2=
=80=9CWow, Facebook, you=E2=80=99re amazing.=E2=80=9D They=E2=80=99re just =
like, =E2=80=9COf course you can do that these days.=E2=80=9D [But] that wa=
sn=E2=80=99t possible 10 years ago. All these stories I hear =E2=80=94 peop=
le reconnecting with lost loved ones, grandparents staying in touch with th=
eir children. Jared Cohen at the State Department said that Facebook=E2=80=
=99s mere existence in its first five years did more to help with relations=
 between Arabs and Israelis than 30 years of coordinated attempts by the CI=
A. This really basic stuff you get from connectivity is so powerful ... but=
 people just take that for granted at this point.Then you do have distracti=
on, filter bubbles, polarization, information privacy, and a lot of problem=
s social media needs to fix. And I=E2=80=99m hopeful. I think these are all=
 fixable problems. You look at industries like tobacco. The difference betw=
een this and tobacco: no matter how you package that product, it=E2=80=99s =
harmful. Whereas social media, if done the right way, if we have a commitme=
nt to making sure the content we=E2=80=99re showing people is relevant to t=
hem, if we=E2=80=99re only sending notifications when something is actually=
 timely and important, the potential is for the pie chart to move very much=
 in the positive direction.&quot;There are solutions to these things,&quot;=
 Rosenstein told me during our chat. Today, Facebook offered up a couple. F=
irst, it took a step to make privacy tools easier to find (https://www.thev=
erge.com/2018/3/28/17171758/facebook-privacy-settings-where-find-mobile-dat=
a). Here's my colleague Ashley Carman:

Most obviously, the privacy settings page now features shortcuts with image=
s to make it easier to navigate, particularly on mobile. Users can enable t=
wo-factor authentication, control what they share or have shared, manage wh=
o can see their posts, and learn more about their ad preferences.The compan=
y=E2=80=99s also launching a new page called =E2=80=9CAccess Your Informati=
on,=E2=80=9D on which users can further evaluate the information they=E2=80=
=99ve shared and manage it. From there, they can delete anything from their=
 timeline or profile that they don=E2=80=99t want on Facebook.Meanwhile Buz=
zFeed had=C2=A0what seems like a brief chat with chief product officer Chri=
s Cox (https://www.buzzfeed.com/alexkantrowitz/facebook-says-if-data-isnt-h=
elping-people-shouldnt-use-it?utm_term=3D.peNeA7Pmk#.cv3oQ27MY).

Cox suggested that Facebook will continue to heavily rely on data for its p=
roducts and services. =E2=80=9CWe want to understand which data is giving p=
eople great experiences in ads, feed, search, messaging, and relevance syst=
ems,=E2=80=9D Cox said. =E2=80=9COn top of that, we should be clear about h=
ow data is used, and offer easy ways to control it.=E2=80=9DSo far, Faceboo=
k has only made a few tiny tweaks in response to the Cambridge Analytica cr=
isis. It=E2=80=99s yet to be seen whether it will simply refurbish the faca=
de of its platform, or if it will rebuild its services from the ground up. =
Referring to the Wednesday=E2=80=99s privacy center announcement, Cox indic=
ated said additional steps are on the way. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s just a sma=
ll step,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s more to come.=E2=80=9D&=
quot;If data isn't helping people, we shouldn't use it,&quot; Cox says else=
where in the piece. It's a philosophical departure from the company's histo=
ric stance of &quot;if data is available, we should build features around i=
t.&quot; The question is now what counts as &quot;helping&quot; people =E2=
=80=94 and to what extent the people being &quot;helped&quot; will have any=
 say in the matter.


